# Engineering Rules

## Startup Tools
- Required quality tools are **pinned**, not floating. Install each tool at the
  exact ref recorded below; never resolve "latest". Bumping a pin is a human
  commit, not an agent action.
- Language tool table:
  - TypeScript: mutation `stryker-mutator` (StrykerJS, version pinned in
    package.json); DRY `jscpd` (pinned in package.json); CRAP computed as
    coverage x cyclomatic complexity from the coverage reporter + complexity
    scripts in `scripts/quality/`.
  - Babashka/Clojure (swarm scripts): mutation/CRAP/DRY tooling is NOT currently
    wired. The Babashka tools this table used to name (`clj-mutate`, `crap4clj`,
    `dry4clj`) are not pinned in `swarmforge.lock.json`, not installed by any
    script, and invoked nowhere â€” so a `.bb` hardening pass has no real
    mutation/CRAP/DRY gate and silently runs the degraded unit-test-gap fallback.
    Today `.bb` swarm scripts are covered by their own unit-test suite
    (`swarmforge/scripts/test/`) ONLY; treat that as the actual gate for swarm
    scripts, not a toolchain that does not exist. Pinning + installing + wiring
    these three tools into the hardener's `.bb` pass is a tracked future item
    (BL-472), deliberately deferred â€” not an active gate. (BL-433 hardening
    surfaced this; the tool table previously implied real `.bb` coverage that
    never existed.)
- APS tools (`gherkin-parser`, `gherkin-mutator`, IR-DRY checker) come from
  `github.com/unclebob/Acceptance-Pipeline-Specification` pinned at
  `accaa33d503340c56513ef387258f8da929ba902`. Prefer the Babashka APS tools;
  use the Go tools only if the Babashka ones fail in this environment. Do not
  reimplement APS commands in the project.

## Design And Testability
- Work in small, reviewable increments.
- Prefer the simplest design that supports the current behavior and leaves clear
  options for the next step.
- Keep tests close to the behavior being changed.
- Separate testable modules from environmentally unsuitable modules. In this
  project the unsuitable boundary is: the VS Code Extension API surface, the
  webview execution context, and live tmux/PTY interaction. Everything else â€”
  socket discovery, `.swarmforge/` state parsing, handoff protocol, grid layout
  logic, backlog parsing â€” must be a testable module reachable without booting
  VS Code.
- Only testable modules participate in tools that run tests: unit tests,
  acceptance tests, coverage, mutation testing, CRAP analysis, DRY analysis that
  invokes tests, and property tests.
- Keep property tests separate from normal verification. Do not include
  property-test tags in normal unit coverage, Gherkin acceptance mutation,
  language mutation, CRAP, or coverage commands unless the role owns
  property-test verification or the user explicitly asks.
- **CLI `main()` is a thin wrapper** over exported, testable helpers; call
  `main()` in-process with stubbed `process.cwd` / `process.argv` / `os.homedir`
  (never `process.chdir()` under mutation). Inject side effects (`postFn` seams),
  not `*_FORCE_RESULT` env bypasses. Ordered-dispatch branches need overlap tests.
  Wiring tests must prove disk reads and CLI failure paths are load-bearing.
- **Detailed rules with incident evidence** (thin-wrapper coverage, mutation
  seams, wiring-test contracts, Vitest isolation, and dozens of other
  hardener-caught patterns) live in
  `swarmforge/constitution/articles/reference/engineering-detailed.prompt`.
  Read that file when your task touches CLIs, subprocess wiring, acceptance step
  handlers, Stryker/mutation, or test isolation â€” not on every boot.

## Test Speed And Isolation
- Keep the unit suite in seconds. **No real timers** (`setTimeout`, `sleep`,
  wall-clock polling). Use fakes for fs, network, tmux, VS Code API, and timers.
- **Stub `process.cwd()` / `os.homedir()`** â€” never `process.chdir()` or
  `process.env.HOME` overlays in worker-thread mutation runs.
- Shell tests: `env -u SWARMFORGE_CONFIG` (and cred vars) before fixture confs.
- Never target the test process with `kill()`; never use `chmod` for failure
  simulation; never diff shared globals (`/tmp`, `ps` broad patterns, live
  runtime paths). Redirect live paths through env seams; missing seam = add one
  in the same parcel.
- Pin fixture clocks when production code reads wall time. Daemon wiring tests:
  override hardcoded timeouts via env seams; tear down on observable exit signals.
- See **engineering-detailed.prompt** for the full incident-backed elaboration.

## Acceptance Pipeline
- APS pinned (see Startup Tools). Features in `specs/features/`; pipeline in
  `specs/pipeline/`. Step handlers drive testable modules, never the VS Code UI.
- Scenario Outline handlers: validate example values against explicit
  `KNOWN_VALUES` â€” no passthrough/binary checks.
- Before deleting a step-handler file, grep all `.feature` files for its patterns.
- See **engineering-detailed.prompt** for Gherkin mutation, lint gates, and
  step-registry deletion rules.

## Verification
- Prefer project-local cache paths in the assigned worktree.
- Run `npm install` after syncing main when `package.json` changed.
- Run acceptance generation and tests sequentially, not concurrently.
- Stryker: Vitest `perTest`, `--mutate` scoped to compiled `out/**/*.js` never
  `src/**/*.ts`. Sandbox sibling symlinks via `ensureStrykerSandboxSiblingLinks`.
- See **engineering-detailed.prompt** for sandbox sweep history and operator
  scoping errors.

## Diagrams
- The project's documentation must include an up-to-date architecture
  diagram, plus any other diagram relevant to understanding the system (the
  project-specific engineering article names which). The documenter owns
  keeping them current: whenever a parcel changes what a diagram depicts,
  the diagram is updated in that documentation pass.
- Diagrams live under `docs/` in a text-based source format (e.g. Mermaid)
  so changes diff, review, and merge like code; no binary-only diagram
  sources.

## Guardrails
- Do not edit mutation or Gherkin mutation manifests by hand.
- Do not commit unrelated local changes or generated artifacts unless required.
- On unexplained session-start reverts, `git restore --source=HEAD --staged
  --worktree -- <paths>` first; never `git stash` for phantom reverts.
- **`swarmforge/scripts/` phantom revert is BL-373 root-caused** â€” hot-sync on
  every launch overwrites branch-only script changes with main; restore and log
  recurrence, do not re-diagnose.
- `extension/out/` is gitignored â€” run `npm run compile` before relying on it.
- Never commit mutation caches. Mailbox dequeue is idempotent against
  completed/abandoned. Quarantine corrupt handoffs at every hop (install,
  deliver, dequeue). GitHub Actions: never interpolate `${{ }}` in `run:` bodies.
- Bounded retries with backoff; lock acquisition loops need max-wait deadlines.
- `grep` enumerate shared-component call sites; confirm-delivery flags arm only
  after send success. Absolutize CLI paths before `cd`. Epic wiring slices must
  have live callers. Three-way drop/deliver/fail gates; idempotent side effects.
- Strip/escape external text embedded in structured files (YAML comments, etc.).
- Rate-limited external syncs: honor 429 `retry_after` on first-tick backfills.
- Optional JSON CLI flags: catch parse errors and degrade to documented fallback.
- See **engineering-detailed.prompt** for full incident narratives on each rule.
